<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910319-0114</DOCNO><DOCID>910319-0114.</DOCID><HL>   Japan Chain Tokyu Wants   Link With Bloomingdale's</HL><DATE>03/19/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C12</SO><CO>   J.TDP T.CMP CMAFC</CO><IN>BROADLINE RETAILERS, DEPARTMENT STORES (RTB)BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)</IN><LP>   TOKYO -- Tokyu Department Store Ltd. said it hopes to linkup with Bloomingdale's Inc. in a move that would give theU.S. retailer its first store in Japan by 1995.   But Federated Department Stores, which ownsBloomingdale's, denied that talks are in progress.</LP><TEXT>   Tokyu and four other Japanese companies plan to develop an&quot;international department store&quot; as part of agovernment-sponsored commercial development project in Chiba,half an hour east of central Tokyo. Tokyu officials stressedthat the plan is still in the works and that Bloomingdale'sis among several Western retailers with whom it is talking.   However, a statement released by Marvin S. Traub,Bloomingdale's chairman, said: &quot;Toyku Department Store is oneof a number of Japanese companies which, over the pastseveral years, have expressed interest in developing somesort of relationship with Bloomingdale's. From time to time,we have had informal conversations with several of them. Atpresent, we are not involved in any formal negotiationstoward such an arrangement, nor do we expect to be involvedin such negotiations in 1991.&quot;   U.S. department store chains have yet to move into thelucrative, but politically tricky, Japanese retail market.   Tokyu, which had estimated sales of 387 billion yen ($2.87billion) in the year ended Jan. 31, has a joint venture inJapan with Williams-Sonoma Inc., the U.S. gourmetkitchen-equipment retailer.</TEXT></DOC>